# Content & Writing Conventions

## Notes Page Content Rules

### Section Numbering
- Always number sections: `1 · Title`, `2 · Title`, etc.
- Sections should flow logically: motivation → definition → mechanics → algorithm → results → extensions.

### Text Prose
- Write in **second or third person** — match the tone of existing pages.
- Keep sentences direct. Avoid padding like "It is important to note that…"
- Use `<span class="term">keyword</span>` for the **first introduction** of a key concept on the page.
- Use `<strong>` for emphasis on critical words — sparingly.
- Use `<em>` for book titles or light emphasis.

### Lists (`<ul>`)
- Use bullet lists (`<ul><li>`) for facts, properties, and comparisons.
- Global CSS already adds `▸` bullets — **never add `list-style` or custom bullets manually**.
- Avoid lists longer than 8 items — split into subsections instead.

### Callouts
Use `.callout` for the single most important insight in a section:
```html
<div class="callout">Key insight text. Use <strong> for the punchline.</div>
```
- One callout per card maximum.
- Never use `.callout` for warnings — it's for positive insights only.

### Formulas
- Every formula must have a `.formula-label` (what it is) and `.formula-main` (the expression).
- Add `.formula-legend` whenever the formula contains symbols a reader might not know.
- Use `<sub>` and `<sup>` for subscripts/superscripts — never Unicode lookalikes.

### Tables
- Use for comparisons (e.g. Algorithm A vs Algorithm B) and hyperparameter reference.
- Every table needs a `<thead>` with `<th>` columns.
- Keep tables to ≤ 8 rows before considering splitting.

### Pros & Cons
Always use the `.reward-grid` pattern from `styles.css`:
```html
<div class="reward-grid">
  <div class="reward-item good"><div class="label">Strengths</div><ul>…</ul></div>
  <div class="reward-item bad"><div class="label">Limitations</div><ul>…</ul></div>
</div>
```

## Module Card on Index Pages

Every card must have all four parts:
```html
<a href="file.html" class="module-card">
  <div class="module-icon">EMOJI</div>       <!-- single emoji, relevant to topic -->
  <div class="module-info">
    <p class="module-tag">Tag · Tag</p>      <!-- 2–4 short tags, · separated -->
    <h2>Topic Title</h2>                     <!-- matches the <h1> of the target page -->
    <p>One sentence. What it covers.</p>     <!-- max 2 lines -->
  </div>
  <span class="module-arrow">›</span>
</a>
```
- `module-tag` content: matches the `<p class="tag">` content of the linked page.
- `<h2>` in the card: identical to (or a shortened form of) the `<h1>` of the target page.
- Description: one sentence, plain English, no jargon without context.

## What NOT to Do

| ❌ Don't | ✅ Do instead |
|---------|--------------|
| Create a new `.css` file | Add page-specific styles in `<style>` in `<head>` |
| Copy `styles.css` into a subfolder | Always use `../styles.css` relative path |
| Add a notes page without updating the index | Always update course `index.html` |
| Use inline `style=""` attributes (except footer link) | Use a class in `<style>` block |
| Override a global class (e.g. redefine `.card`) | Add a new modifier class |
| Use `<br>` for spacing | Use margin/padding in CSS |
| Use emoji in `<h1>` or `<h2>` headings | Use `<span class="icon">EMOJI</span>` inside `<h2>` only |
| Leave a `<div class="section-divider">` without a `.card` after it | Always pair them |
